qas.question: What is the formal name of the Interstate Highway System?

answers.text: Dwight D. Eisenhower National System of Interstate and Defense Highways

qas.question: Along with Germany and Switzerland, what country contained an autobahn during the Second World War?
When were "Eisenhower Interstate System" signs first posted along highways?
What is another name for Eisenhower Expressway?
What major city is Interstate 290 close to?

context: The Interstate Highway System is officially known as the '<a0_0>Dwight D. Eisenhower National System of Interstate and Defense Highways<a0_0/>' in his honor. It was inspired in part by Eisenhower's own Army experiences in World War II, where he recognized the advantages of the autobahn systems in Germany, <a1_0>Austria<a1_0/>, and Switzerland. Commemorative signs reading "Eisenhower Interstate System" and bearing Eisenhower's permanent 5-star rank insignia were introduced in <a2_0>1993<a2_0/> and are currently displayed throughout the Interstate System. Several highways are also named for him, including the Eisenhower Expressway (<a3_0>Interstate 290<a3_0/>) near <a4_0>Chicago<a4_0/> and the Eisenhower Tunnel on Interstate 70 west of Denver.
